Mount Apo was first successfully climbed in 1880 by Joaquin Rajal, Governor of Davao, Joseph Montano, a French anthropologist, and Jesuit missionary Father Mateo Gisbert, among others. The mountain was declared a national park on May 9, 1936, by President Manuel L. Quezon.

Mount Apo is a biodiversity hotspot, home to over 272 bird species, 111 of which are endemic to the area. It is also the habitat of the critically endangered Philippine eagle, the country's national bird. The mountain has four major lakes, including Lake Venado, a popular camping site for mountaineers. Additionally, Mount Apo is a headwaters catchment area for several major river systems in the region.